---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import NewsletterSignup from '../../components/NewsletterSignup.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="What to Say When: A Field Guide for Sports Parents"
  description="A free 28-page field guide. Twenty-three scripts for the moments before and after the game, and the hard ones in between. By age, calibrated for the car and the kitchen."
>
  <section class="border-b border-ink bg-ink text-paper">
    <div class="container-px py-20 grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10 items-end">
      <div class="md:col-span-7">
        <p class="font-display italic text-trophy mb-3 font-medium">Free · 28 pages · PDF</p>
        <h1 class="font-display text-paper text-[2.5rem] md:text-[4.5rem] leading-[1.0] font-medium">
          What to Say <em class="text-rust">When</em>.
        </h1>
        <p class="font-display text-paper-warm text-xl md:text-2xl mt-8 max-w-xl leading-snug">
          A field guide for sports parents. Twenty-three scripts for the moments before and after the game, and the hard ones in between. Calibrated by age, for the car, the kitchen, the parking lot.
        </p>
        <p class="font-display italic text-paper-warm mt-6 text-base font-medium">
          Drop your email below. We'll send you the PDF and add you to the weekly note. Easy unsubscribe.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-5">
        <NewsletterSignup
          variant="card"
          headline="Send me the field guide"
          blurb="One subscribe, two things in your inbox: the field guide now, and one short read a week from the editorial desk."
          buttonLabel="Send the field guide"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-b border-bone">
    <div class="container-px py-16 grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-4">
        <p class="font-display italic text-rust font-medium">What's inside</p>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 article-body">
        <p>Twenty-three scripts, organized into three parts. Each one follows the same pattern: what your kid is probably feeling, three things you can say, three you shouldn't, the rule underneath, and what to do if they bring it up.</p>
        <p><strong>Before the game.</strong> Seven scripts: by age (5–7, 8–10, 11–12, 13–14), plus the nervous kid, the championship game, and the summer tryout.</p>
        <p><strong>After the game.</strong> Nine scripts: by age, plus the win, the loss, the bad game, the mistake, and the bench.</p>
        <p><strong>The hard moments.</strong> Seven scripts: silence in the car, tears in the parking lot, the teammate's injury everyone watched, the post-cut text, the captain pick that stung, the meltdown at practice, the end of the season.</p>
        <p>Plus a tri-fold pocket card to cut and fold into the glove box.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-b border-bone">
    <div class="container-px py-16 grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-4">
        <p class="font-display italic text-rust font-medium">Why we made it</p>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 article-body">
        <p>The most important sentences a parent says about their kid's sport happen in two narrow windows. The minute before the game. The first ninety seconds after. Most parents wing it. Most parents wish they hadn't.</p>
        <p>The fix is small. A different sentence. A different tone. A pattern that works the same at 8 and at 14. We wrote it down.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <NewsletterSignup
    headline="Send the playbook"
    blurb="One short note a week, plus the playbook in your inbox right now."
    buttonLabel="Get the Friday Letter"
  />
</BaseLayout>
